    <text>
        <body><div type="bibliography">
                
                <p><bibl><ptr target="#boardman-hayes1973"/>, p. 85, n. <citedRange>2195</citedRange> (dr.)</bibl>;
                    <bibl><ptr target="#IGCyr"/> <citedRange>004300</citedRange></bibl>.</p>
            </div><div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">
                
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" rend="right-to-left"/><w lemma="πύαλoς">πύα<supplied reason="omitted" cert="low">λος</supplied></w>
	 </ab>
            </div><div type="apparatus" xml:space="preserve">
            
                <p>
                    <app loc="1">
                        <rdg resp="#boardman-hayes1973">πύα<supplied reason="omitted">λος</supplied></rdg>
                            <rdg resp="#boardman-hayes1973">πυ<subst><del rend="corrected">ρ</del><add place="overstrike">λ</add></subst></rdg>
                    </app>
               </p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="fr">
            <p>Bassin pour le bain (?)</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="en">
            <p>Bath tub (?)</p>
            </div><div type="translation" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="it">
            <p>Bacino per il bagno (?)</p>
            </div><div type="commentary">
                
                <p>The reading <foreign xml:lang="grc">πύαλoς</foreign> would give an interesting word. However, what has a bath-tub to do with a kalathos?</p>
	           <p>The lettering might be Cyrenaean as well as Attic.</p>
	<p/>
            </div></body>
    </text>
